  

<p>Iâ€™ve used âŒ˜-hover on my Mac to preview internal links in Obsidian for years, but this week I discovered that it also works on tabs. Quite by accident I held down <code>âŒ˜</code> while hovering over the name of a tab, and a 3rd-party-plugin-free, scrollable preview of that page appeared â€” with clickable links (!).</p>
<p>I turned off the Hover Editor plugin back in the day because I found its behaviour inconsistent and annoying. And anyway, I prefer plugin-free solutions wherever feasible.</p>
<p>So far Iâ€™ve used âŒ˜-hover over tabs to quickly view the today page, while looking at my tasks for this week.</p>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/29c3712a-aff1-47f3-a7b8-6d37115ae0ef.jpg" alt="Mac screenshot showing a popup window with a grey background coming from a tab on a page in Obsidian" width="2109" height="1611"></p>
<p>Pressing âŒ˜ (âŒƒ in Windows) while hovering over tabs does what I want and nothing more: it makes the target page appear as a functional window on top of the current page, and disappear when the mouse moves away from it.</p>
<p>Command/Control-hovering over tabs works well for plugin-free, basic previews of both tabs and internal links. Any links you click in this preview will replace the current page. âŒ˜-hovering over links in the preview popup window will overlay another preview window of that link.</p>
<p>The Hover Editor plugin allows you to see a persistent, editable, resizable window on top of the current page, but links clicked here will open another Hover Editor window, leaving the current page in place. Command/Control-clicking these links will cause them to open in the place of the current page.</p>
<h3 id="how-to-use-notebook-navigator">How to use Notebook Navigator</h3>
<p>Elizabeth Tai recently released a <a href="https://elizabethtai.com/2025/11/25/how-to-use-notebook-navigator-obsidian-community-plug-in/" target="_blank">handy resource</a> for using the Notebook Navigator plugin in Obsidian. She is a technical writer by trade, so the information is clearly set out and easy to follow.</p>
<p>Do you use this plugin? Find it helpful? For where I am today, itâ€™s feeling a bit too <a href="https://ellanew.com/2025/11/24/ptpl-183-the-3-levels-of-plain-text-productivity" title="wikilink">level-3</a>. Same with Bases.</p>
